<h1>From Richard Henry Lee</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Philadelphia Novemr 13th 1775</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I must beg leave at the beginning of this letter to apologise for any incorrectness as I write in great hasteIndeed the hurry of business is such here with many of us, that we have little time for the ordinary offices of life.</p>
<p>You may be assured that I will do Colo. Read all the service that I can in the way you desire.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> We have a Ship here in 6 weeks from London, that brought the original letter of which the inclosed is a copy. Tis from a well informed, sensible friend, and may be relyed on.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> All the other letters from London join in confirming it to be the fixt determination of K<span class="space" title="space in original source" style="padding-left:2px; padding-right:2px;">[      ]</span><a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> and Court to leave undone, nothing that they can do, to compel implicit obedience in America. One very sensible letter that I have seen, mentions that Gen. Amherst<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> had recommended (&amp; twas said it would be executed) to remove the Army this winter from Boston to Long Island, in order to get amply supplied by ravaging N. Jersey, N. York, and Rhode Island. Should this be attempted, I suppose you will be furnished with an opportunity of giving them a genteel parting salute. And besides, I should suppose that a winter favorable for us, would expose them to ruin from a timely, strong attack, of superior numbers on that naked Island. It seems that immense stores of Indian goods are sent to Canada in order to bribe the Indians to an early and vigorous attack on all our frontiers next Spring. God grant that Colo. Arnolds success and Montgomeries may frustrate this diabolical part of their infernal plan against the common natural rights of Mankind!</p>
<p>We hoped here that the surrender of Chambl, with the military stores there obtained, would speedily procure the reduction of St Johns, but no accounts are yet come of this wished event.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> After Lord Dunmore, supported by the North British Tories, had long committed every outrage at Norfolk unopposed,
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0364">[364]</span>
our people not having Arms or ammunition until lately; his Banditti at length attempted Hampton, where they met with the chastisement you will see described in the part of Dixons paper inclosed. The Lieutenant Wright there mentioned has been since found dead on the Shore, a bullet having been placed in his body before he jumpt over board.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> We have not yet heard the consequence of their next intended attack, but it seems a very heavy Cannonade was heared there the next day. If the Devil inspired them to come on shore, I make no doubt but we shall have a good account of them. I have a very particular reason for entreating that you will inform me by return of Post, what number, and what strength of Armed Vessels could possibly be procured from the ports where you are, to be in Delaware Bay, if Congress should desire it, by the middle or last of December at furthest. Two or 3 Vessels of tolerable force, issuing from hence, may affect a stroke or two of great consequence to us at that Season. We have certainly 4000 weight of powder, and a very considerable quantity of Oznaburgs arrived in Virginia from Statia<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0007" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> for the use of our little Army consisting of about 2000 men now at Williamsburg &amp; HamptonBe pleased to let Gen. Lee see the letter from England.</p>
<p>I heartily wish you every happiness and all the success the goodness of your cause deserves, &amp; I am, with great esteem dear Sir Your affect. friend and obedient servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Richard Henry Lee</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>Congress has ordered 500,000 dollars to you soon as they can be signed.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0008" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0008-ptr">8</a></p>
<p>The Continental, and Virginia Commissioners, have just concluded a treaty of firm friendship with the Ohio Indians and those of the Six nations that inhabit near that Quarter.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0009" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0009-ptr">9</a> We have taken the most effectual measures, by sending runners from all the Southern provinces into the Indian Nations thro which he proposes to pass, to arrest and secure Ld Dunmores wicked Agent Conelly.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0010" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0010-ptr">10</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0233" class="document">GW to Richard Henry Lee, 29 Oct. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The unidentified writer of this letter of 4 Sept. reports that the quantity of Artillery, Arms &amp; ammunition shipd agst N. England is greater than ever went from this Country before. These, with an Army of 24,000 Men are intended
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0365">[365]</span>
to carry destruction thro those provinces next Spring. Fifty ships of War are to ravage the Coast &amp; interdict all Commerce. Small Armies are to be sent to Virginia &amp; So. Carolina. It will behoove them [the Americans] therefore to prepare against the Storm that is intended to pour down destruction upon them. The writer also discusses the kings proclamation forbidding correspondence with the rebelling colonists and Parliaments refusal to answer Congresss recent petition, and he warns caution in opening American ports to all countries. It would, he wrote, hazard the uniting the Country against America, &amp; unless there is a certainty of its being accepted by other Nations, might be injurious (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>King.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0004">4</a>
  
   <p><span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from 'Jeffery' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2008-09-25]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">Jeffrey</span> Amherst (17171797), who served as commander in chief in America during the French and Indian War, supported the ministrys policy toward America and acted throughout the war as a leading adviser to the government on military matters.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>News of the surrender of St. Jean on 2 Nov. reached Congress on 14 November.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>The clipping from John Dixon and William Hunters <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Virginia Gazette</span> for 28 Oct. includes an account of the unsuccessful attempt by a British naval squadron to burn Hampton between 25 and 27 Oct. and an order of the Virginia committee of safety forbidding entry into Norfolk and Portsmouth without permission in order to prevent provisions and intelligence from reaching Lord Dunmores forces (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). Lt. John Wright commanded one of the tenders in the squadron that attacked Hampton.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>Saint Eustatius.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>Congress authorized these funds on 11 Nov. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span>,</span> 3:352).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>This treaty was concluded at Fort Pitt on 23 October.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0336-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>See the Virginia Delegates to the Williamsburg Committee of Safety, 23 Oct. 1775, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Paul H. Smith et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Letters of Delegates to Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;. 26 vols. Washington, D.C., 19762000. ]">Smith, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letters of Delegates</span></span>, 2:24142.</p>

</div>
